1 public works improvements, and facilities required to accommodate new construction or
2 development; and
3 WHEREAS, The Supreme Court of the United States, in Sheetz v. County of El
4 Dorado, 601 U.S. ____ (2024), held that local government permit conditions (1) must have
5 an “essential nexus” to the government’s land use interests, and “rough proportionality” to
6 the development’s impact on the land use interest; and (2) may not require a landowner to
7 give up or pay more than is necessary to mitigate harms caused from new development;
8 now, therefore,
9 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
10 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
11 Article – Local Government
12 20–125.
13 (A) THIS SECTION APPLIES ONLY TO A COUNTY THAT:
14 (1) IS A CHARTER COUNTY THAT IMPOSES, BY LAW, DEVELOPMENT
15 FEES, SURCHARGES, OR EXCISE TAXES;
16 (2) IS A CODE COUNTY WITH PUBLIC LOCAL LAWS THAT REQUIRE THE
17 PAYMENT OF DEVELOPMENT IMPACT FEES, SURCHARGES, OR EXCISE TAXES; OR
18 (3) IS A COMMISSION COUNTY THAT:
19 (I) HAS BEEN AUTHORIZED TO ENACT DEVELOPMENT IMPACT
20 FEES, SURCHARGES, OR EXCISE TAXES; AND
21 (II) HAS ENACTED, BY LOCAL LAW, DEVELOPMENT IMPACT
22 FEES, SURCHARGES, OR EXCISE TAXES.
23 (B) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1 EACH YEAR, EACH COUNTY SHALL REPORT TO
24 THE GOVERNOR AND THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF
25 THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION RELATING TO
26 THE COLLECTION AND EXPENDITURE OF DEVELOPMENT IMPACT FEES,
27 SURCHARGES, OR EXCISE TAXES FOR THE PRIOR CALENDAR YEAR:
28 (1) THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF DEVELOPMENT IMPACT FEES,
29 SURCHARGES, OR EXCISE TAXES PAID BY NEW CONSTRUCTION OR DEVELOPMENT
30 PROJECTS;

